\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 are continuous distributions.
 Without loss of generality, 
\begin_inset Formula $EG=ES=0$
\end_inset

.
 People pair according to an attractiveness function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A(g_{i},s_{i})=f((1-k)g_{i},ks_{i})
\]

\end_inset

which is smooth and strictly increasing in both its arguments.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

indifference curves
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of attractiveness are vertical lines in 
\begin_inset Formula $(G,S)$
\end_inset

 space.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

, they are horizontal lines.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 they are arbitrary downward sloping curves.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Write 
\begin_inset Formula $p(i)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's partner.
 We assume the population has positive measure on each attractiveness curve.
 Thus, pairs always have the same attractiveness.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A(g_{i},s_{i})=A(g_{p(i)},s_{p(i)}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each pair has two children.
 We assume that both children 
\begin_inset Formula $c(d)$
\end_inset

 of parents 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
g_{c(d)} & =\frac{g_{d}+g_{m}}{2};\label{eq:children-average}\\
s_{c(d)} & =\frac{s_{d}+s_{m}}{2}.\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a strong assumption; we relax it later.
 For real world examples approximated by it, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 could be wealth which is equally divided between the children; 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 could be a highly polygenic trait with many small effects.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{p},S_{p}$
\end_inset

 to denote the population variables in the parents' generation; 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{c},S_{c}$
\end_inset

 for the children's generation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
PROPOSITION:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(i) 
\begin_inset Formula $Cov(G_{c},S_{c})\ge Cov(G_{p},S_{p})$
\end_inset

, with strict inequality if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $0<k<1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(ii) If 
\begin_inset Formula $corr(G_{p},S_{p})\ge0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $corr(G_{c},S_{c})\ge corr(G_{p},S_{p})$
\end_inset

, with strict inequality if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $0<k<1$
\end_inset

 
\bar under
or
\bar default
 
\begin_inset Formula $corr(G_{p},S_{p})>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
PROOF:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Within each pair 
\begin_inset Formula $i,p(i)$
\end_inset

 write 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 for the person with 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{d}>s_{p(d)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $p(d)$
\end_inset

.
 (Think of these as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dukes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

milkmaids
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, or if you prefer 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

duchesses
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tennis instructors
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.) If 
\begin_inset Formula $k<1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{d}<g_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 (If 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

, then define 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 as the person with 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{d}<g_{p(d)}$
\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We integrate over the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dukes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to calculate the covariance in the parents' generation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
cov(G_{p},S_{p})=\int\frac{1}{2}(g_{d}s_{d}+g_{p(d)}s_{p(d)})\,\mathrm{d}d.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the children, the equivalent expression is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
cov(G_{c},S_{c})=\int g_{c(d)}s_{c(d)}\mathrm{d}d,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
observing that 
\begin_inset Formula $EG_{c}=ES_{c}=0$
\end_inset

 from (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:children-average"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Take an arbitrary pair 
\begin_inset Formula $d,m$
\end_inset

.
 Write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
g_{d}s_{d} & =(g_{c}-\Delta g)(s_{c}+\Delta s);\\
g_{m}s_{m} & =(g_{c}+\text{\ensuremath{\Delta g)(s_{c}-\Delta s)}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{\ensuremath{\Delta g=\frac{g_{m}-g_{d}}{2}\ge0}}, & \textrm{strictly so if and only if }k>0;\\
\Delta s=\frac{s_{d}-s_{m}}{2}\ge0 & \textrm{strictly so if and only if }k<1.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the average of the parents gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{2}(g_{d}s_{d}+g_{m}s_{m})=g_{c}s_{c}-\Delta g\Delta s.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{c}s_{c}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $0<k<1$
\end_inset

, and equal to it if 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

.
 Plugging this into the integral shows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
cov(G_{p},S_{p})\le cov(G_{c},S_{c})
\]

\end_inset

again with strict inequality if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $0<k<1$
\end_inset

.
 This proves the first part.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
corr(G_{j},S_{j})=\frac{cov(G_{j},S_{j})}{\sqrt{var(G_{j})var(S_{j})}}\textrm{ for both generations }j\in\{p,c\}.\label{eq:corr-cov-var}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
var(G_{p}) & =\frac{1}{2}\int g_{d}^{2}+g_{p(d)}^{2}\textrm{d}d;\\
var(G_{c}) & =\int g_{c(d)}^{2}\textrm{d}d.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Much as before,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
g_{d}^{2}+g_{m}^{2} & =(g_{c}-\Delta g)^{2}+(g_{c}+\Delta g)^{2}\\
 & =2g_{c}^{2}+2(\Delta g)^{2}\\
 & \ge2g_{c}^{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $var(G_{c})\le var(G_{p})$
\end_inset

 and a similar argument shows 
\begin_inset Formula $var(S_{c})\le var(S_{p})$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the covariance is higher (and positive) in the children's generation,
 while the variances are lower.
 Combining these ensures that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
corr(G_{c},S_{c})\ge corr(G_{p},S_{p}).
\]

\end_inset

Since for any 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, either 
\begin_inset Formula $var(G_{c})<var(G_{p})$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $var(S_{c})\le var(S_{p})$
\end_inset

, the only way to get strict equality for the above is if 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $cov(G_{c},S_{c})=cov(G_{p},S_{p})=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To show that the condition in the second part cannot be relaxed further,
 consider the distribution in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Correlation-counterexample"

\end_inset

.
 There is negative correlation in the parents' generation (the shaded area).
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

 or is close enough to 0, then mating along the dotted lines will reduce
 the variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 along those lines, without affecting the covariance.
 This will make the correlation more negative.
 After repeated generations the horizontal variance will almost disappear
 and the correlation will approach -1.
\end_layout

