\begin_layout Standard
We now weaken the condition that children are exactly at the mean of their
 parents' values for 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
g_{c(i)} & =\bar{g}_{i}+\varepsilon_{i}^{G}\\
s_{c(i)} & =\bar{s}_{i}+\varepsilon_{i}^{S}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{g}_{i}=\frac{g_{i}+g_{p(i)}}{2};\bar{s}_{i}=\frac{s_{i}+s_{p(i)}}{2}
\]

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon^{G}$
\end_inset

 has mean 0 and variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{G}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon^{S}$
\end_inset

 has mean 0 and variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{S}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This condition is fulfilled for 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 for most kinds of genetic variation, including polygenic traits and single-gene
 locuses with additive variance.
